Red Star Express Plc, has recorded a 19 per cent decline in its after-tax profit for third quarter (Q3), ended December 31, 2019 according to details of the company’s financials released on the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE).  It financial result revealed that profit after tax dipped to N100.643 million from N123.557 million in Q3, 2018. Profit before tax also declined to N148.004 million as against N534.000 million in the corresponding period of 2018, while earnings per share dropped to 17 kobo from 21 kobo. Turnover dipped by two per cent to N2.624 billion in the review period compared to the N2.677 posted in the corresponding period of 2018, cost of sales went down to N1.996 billion, compared to N2.015 billion achieved in 2018, while gross profit stood at N627.852 million from N661.725 million. Finance Costs soared by 109.5 per cent from N8.260 million at Q3 2018 to N17.308 million in the relative period of 2019, contributing in part to the decline in profit. Red Star Express, which owns the FedEx franchise, currently trades on the floor of the NSE at N4.45 per share as at January 28, 2020. Speaking at the company annual general meeting (AGM) held in June, 2019, the chairman, board of directors of Red Star, Mr Suleiman Barau said the company recorded impressive figures amidst challenges in the Nigerian economy. He stated that the Nigerian business terrain remains one of the most challenging in Africa, saying that “But in spite of these challenges, I am happy to inform you that the last financial year was successful as the company reported impressive figures across all our performance indicators.” The group managing director of the company, Mr Olusola Obabori, added, “We are, however, hopeful that this year, we will record a higher turnover than last year. Red Star Express is committed to wealth for shareholders, and appreciates their support at all times.”